20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uskyjim.showPublicProfile?language=EN>skyjim</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Lurker</span><br>  Posts: 1<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(8/13/02 1:16 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm3.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=99.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Own a telescope?</span><hr size=1> Hamster, I've been using scopes since the late 80s.  I've been mostly a large newtonian enthusiast, with a &quot;minor&quot; in apochromatic refractors, but also own a Nexstar 11 Schmidt-Cassegrain.<br>
<br>
Collimation isn't really difficult, but if you have an SCT or a newtonian you do need to at least check collimation every time you set up to insure that your scope is performing at its best.  I've seen many unhappy scope owners over the years who started loving their scopes once they learned how to collimate them properly!<br>
<br>
Commercial SCTs from Meade and Celestron allow only one collimation adjustment, the tilt of the secondary mirror.  Newtonians typically allow secondary tilt, rotation, and axial position adjustment as well as primary mirror tilt.  If you want to be technical, most also allow focuser base adjustments, seldom done by most owners, but if the focuser isn't squared up to the optical tube, you can do something about it in a newtonian.  <br>
<br>
SCTs typically have image shift when focusing, due to the fact that they focus by moving the primary mirror.  Some people find it extremely annoying during visual use, and it can be a real problem if you image, but it doesn't bother me much in my 11.<br>
<br>
My experience is that SCTs tend to hold collimation a bit better than commercial newtonians in most cases.  Tradeoffs are cost, field of view, ease of setup, and compactness.  Although dobsonians are <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    bulkier</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> than SCTs of the same aperture, they are actually much quicker and easier to set up IMHO.  SCTs over 8 inches get fairly heavy, and you must mount the heavy and expensive tube/base assembly on the tripod, hoping to line things up properly while essentially working blind.  The tube/base on my Nexstar 11 weighs 65 pounds, and that is about as much as I care to lift while trying to precisely line up on a locating pin that I cannot see.  An 8 inch is much more manageable.  <br>
<br>
One issue for me with the classic 8 inch SCTs is the inability to use 2 inch wide field eyepieces to full advantage.  The optical system cuts off light to the outer portion of the field of view of most low power 2 inch eyepieces even when you install a thread-on 2 inch diagonal.  The standard Schmidt accessory thread is about 1.5 inches in clear aperture, and the baffle tube on which the primary mirror slides is about the same diameter in the 8 inchers and is in the light path from the  secondary to the eyepiece.  I've gotten spoiled by the way 2 inch eyepieces make the scope just get out of your way and give the impression that you're looking through a porthole at space instead of seeing through the bottom of a long tube.  An 8 inch dob with a two inch focuser does not have this problem if properly designed.<br>
<br>
I'd advise thinking about what you wish to do with the scope, especially whether you wish to do any kind of imaging.  If so, you can discard the dobsonians.  There are equatorial platforms for dobs, but they eat up the price advantage.  If you're looking at bang for the buck, you simply cannot beat a dobsonian reflector for visual work.  There are good ones out there!  The Orion XT-8 is an 8&quot; f6, a different tube from the one Atomic had, and doesn't share the rickety mount.  Most budget equatorial mounts are junk IMO, which is why I tend to steer beginners away from them.  I've seen a number of XT-8s which throw up very nice images.  There are lots of other manufacturers out there - Discovery comes to mind, a U.S. built scope which is a little more expensive  but uses Pyrex for the primary mirror instead of soda-lime glass.<br>
<br>
  The Chinese and Taiwanese built dobs are a good value in the more moderate focal ratios.   Producing a good mirror at f5.5 or f6 is <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i>    much</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> easier than producing a good one at f4.5, and the shorter f-ratios are also much more sensitive to collimation errors and have significant coma at the edge of the field.  You're probably more likely to be happy with an asian-sourced budget reflector with an f-ratio above  5.0 than one at 4.5.  Around f6 coma becomes a non-factor for most people, and the scope is also much more tolerant of minor collimation errors than an f4.5 instrument.  This means a longer tube in a newtonian, but for dobs in the 8 inch range, it gets the eyepiece up to a more comfortable height  for seated observing.  As long as you're not trying to fit the scope into a really tiny vehicle, an 8 inch f6 shouldn't pose transport problems.<br>
<br>
<br>
U.S. built scopes also have their share of troubles.  My buddy has had to send his LX-90 back to Meade twice for circuit board replacements.  He still loves the scope, but it hasn't been as trouble-free as Atomic's.  Just luck of the draw in mass produced instruments, methinks.  <br>
<br>
Clear Skies!<br>
<br>
Jim<br>
<br>
Edit: Forgot to answer your favorite targets query.  Hell, I enjoy everything, but in an 8 incher I recommend the bright planets, especially Jupiter and Saturn, the moon (you'll probably want a moon filter) at less than quarter-phase, and all of the Messier objects.  I highly recommend the use of a reflex finder like a Rigel Qwikfinder as an aid to learning the sky.  You can get some very nice books for use with reflex finders which show the bulls-eye of the finder properly placed against star background for each Messier object.  I'll post links if you are interested.     J <br>
